e show a pronounced latitudinal increase in phytoplanktonic and zooplanktonic biodiversity in the extratropical North Atlantic Ocean in recent decades. We also show that this rise in biodiversity paralleled a decrease in the mean size of zooplanktonic copepods and that the reorganization of the planktonic ecosystem toward dominance by smaller organisms may influence the networks in which carbon flows, with negative effects on the downward biological carbon pump and demersal Atlantic cod (Gadus morhua). Our study suggests that, contrary to the usual interpretation of increasing biodiversity being a positive emergent property promoting the stability/resilience of ecosystems, the parallel decrease in sizes of planktonic organisms could be viewed in the North Atlantic as reducing some of the services provided by marine ecosystems to humans.","Biodiversity; Carbon cycles; Climate change; Ecosystem services; Fisheries","carbon; article; Atlantic cod; Atlantic Ocean; biodiversity; copepod; ecosystem; greenhouse effect; marine environment; nonhuman; priority journal; Animals; Atlantic Ocean; Biodiversity; Body Size; Carbon; Climate Change; Copepoda; Diatoms; Dinoflagellida; Ecosystem; Gadus morhua; Marine Biology; Models, Biological; Phytoplankton; Zooplankton; Copepoda; Gadus morhua",,"carbon, 7440-44-0; Carbon, 7440-44-0",,,,"(2007) Climate Change 2007: Impacts, Adaptation and Vulnerability, , Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change WGI (Cambridge Univ Press, Cambridge, UK); Barnett, T.P., Penetration of human-induced warming into the world's oceans (2005) Science, 309, pp. 284-287; Levitus, S., Antonov, J., Boyer, T., Warming of the world ocean, 1955-2003 (2005) Geophys Res Lett, 32, pp. L02604; Brown, J.H., Gillooly, J.F., Allen, A.P., Savage, V.M., West, G.B., Toward a metabolic theory of ecology (2004) Ecology, 85, pp. 1771-1789; Beaugrand, G., Luczak, C., Edwards, M., Rapid biogeographical plankton shifts in the North Atlantic Ocean (2009) Glob Change Biol, 15, pp.